    },
    {
      "id": "R1-F06",
      "severity": "medium",
      "category": "testing",
      "file": "src/tests/advance-records.test.ts",
      "title": "No test for record write failure causing transition failure",
      "detail": "The spec states 'if the record write fails, the transition SHALL also fail'. While advance-records.test.ts exists (untracked), verify it includes a test where records.write() throws and confirm the transition returns an error rather than proceeding. The current advance.ts code does not wrap records.write() in try/catch — an unhandled throw would propagate but produce an unstructured error rather than a CoreRuntimeError.",
      "origin_round": 1,
      "latest_round": 1,
      "status": "resolved",
      "relation": "new",
      "supersedes": null,
      "notes": "",
      "resolved_round": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "R1-F07",
      "severity": "low",
      "category": "quality",
      "file": "src/core/advance.ts",
      "title": "nextRecordSequence relies on list().length which is fragile",
      "detail": "nextRecordSequence computes sequence as `records.list(runId).length + 1`. If a record is ever deleted (the store interface supports delete), sequence numbers will collide. Consider using a monotonic counter or max-sequence scan instead of list length. Low severity because delete is unlikely during normal flow, but the spec does define a delete operation.",
      "origin_round": 1,
      "latest_round": 1,
      "status": "resolved",
      "relation": "new",
      "supersedes": null,
      "notes": "",
      "resolved_round": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "R2-F08",
      "severity": "medium",
      "category": "testing",
      "file": "src/tests/advance-records.test.ts",
      "title": "No integration tests for ClarifyRecord creation or resolution in advance flow",
      "detail": "advance-records.test.ts thoroughly tests ApprovalRecord creation, approval, rejection, record_ref in history, backward compat, and write failure — but has zero tests for ClarifyRecord flows. The clarify_request → pending ClarifyRecord and clarify_response → resolved ClarifyRecord paths in advance.ts (lines 219-258) are untested at the integration level. Add tests that: (1) issue a clarify_request event and verify a pending ClarifyRecord is created with correct phase/question, (2) issue a clarify_response event and verify the pending ClarifyRecord is resolved with the answer, (3) verify record_ref appears in history for clarify transitions.",
      "origin_round": 2,
      "latest_round": 2,
      "status": "new",
      "relation": "new",
      "supersedes": null,
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "R2-F09",
      "severity": "low",
      "category": "correctness",
      "file": "src/core/advance.ts",
      "title": "nextRecordSequence parsing is fragile when runId contains hyphens",
      "detail": "nextRecordSequence splits record_id on '-' and takes the last segment as the sequence number. Given the format '<kind>-<runId>-<sequence>' and a runId like 'my-feature-1', the record_id 'approval-my-feature-1-1' splits to ['approval','my','feature','1','1']. The last segment '1' happens to be correct, but if the runId itself ends with a number (e.g., 'run-42'), record_id 'approval-run-42-3' would parse '3' correctly. The approach works by accident because the sequence is always the final segment, but it would be more robust to use lastIndexOf('-') instead of split. Low severity since the current format guarantees the sequence is last.",
      "origin_round": 2,
      "latest_round": 2,
      "status": "new",
      "relation": "new",
      "supersedes": null,
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "R2-F10",
      "severity": "low",
      "category": "quality",
      "file": "src/core/advance.ts",
      "title": "Record write failure does not prevent state write — atomicity gap",
      "detail": "If a record write succeeds but the subsequent writeRunState (line 291) fails, the record has been persisted but the run state hasn't been updated, leaving an orphaned record. Conversely, the try-catch on lines 157-266 correctly prevents state writes when record writes fail. This is a minor concern since writeRunState failures would throw and propagate, and orphaned records are relatively benign. However, the proposal states 'event emission and record creation that atomic' — full atomicity would require transactional writes or compensation. Low severity as filesystem writes rarely fail partially and the current behavior is acceptable.",
      "origin_round": 2,
      "latest_round": 2,
      "status": "new",
      "relation": "new",
      "supersedes": null,
      "notes": ""
    }
  ],
